@page "/"

<PageTitle>EPIC 00: Repo Retrofit</PageTitle>

<div class="epic-banner">
    <h1>EPIC 00: Repo Retrofit (Blazor WebAssembly)</h1>
    <p class="epic-intro">
        This Blazor WebAssembly app lives entirely under the <code>app/</code> directory and is wired for an
        agent-driven workflow with supporting folders at the repository root.
    </p>
</div>

<section class="repo-overview">
    <h2>Repository Structure (Developer Quick View)</h2>
    <p>
        The primary UI for this epic is the documentation and repo layout. For full details, see the root
        <code>README.md</code> and <code>logs/CHANGELOG.md</code>. At a glance:
    </p>

    <ul class="repo-layout-list">
        <li><code>app/</code> – Blazor WebAssembly application (all app code, pages, and assets).</li>
        <li><code>agents/</code> – Agent definitions and configuration placeholders.</li>
        <li><code>tasks/</code> – EPIC/task definition files (e.g., <code>EPIC_00_MVP.md</code>).</li>
        <li><code>logs/</code> – Log artifacts and <code>CHANGELOG.md</code> for summarized changes.</li>
        <li><code>docs/</code> – Additional project documentation.</li>
        <li><code>db/</code> – Data storage and local database files (if/when used).</li>
    </ul>

    <p class="note">
        To run the app locally, follow the instructions in the root <code>README.md</code>
        (starting with <code>cd app</code> then <code>dotnet run</code>).
    </p>
</section>

<section class="epic-notes">
    <h2>EPIC 00 Scope Notes</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Focus is on repository structure and documentation, not new UI features.</li>
        <li>All runtime and configuration changes for the Blazor app stay under <code>app/</code>.</li>
        <li>No <code>frontend/</code> or <code>backend/</code> directories are used for the UI.</li>
    </ul>
</section>
